snippet.title: "Freedom of Speech" - Marsh Family parody of "Under the Sea" from Disney's "The Little Mermaid"
snippet.description:
We couldn't find any lobster costumes, and a whirling freestyle in the middle of a school week was not gonna happen. So - with some extra input from a few media sources to cover instrumental sections - this is our parody rendition of "Under the Sea", one of our old Disney favourites for its sheer joy and energy. It was composed by Alan Menken (with cracking lyrics by Howard Ashman) for the 1989 animated "The Little Mermaid" and won an Oscar. Of course, the calypso lobster's forlorn plea for an alternative path falls on deaf ears. Which brings us to free speech.

It's been a scary time in lots of ways in the US, with the temperature cranked up again by shocking murders and reckless responses, and sadly now the First Amendment (for decades a place of some bipartisan accord) seems to be creaking. As we were working on the arrangement, we learned that Jimmy Kimmel's show had been reinstated by Disney - which is great news, having loved meeting him in 2020 albeit under bizarre pandemic circumstances - though we gather that much is still unclear about how the matter is going to play out. Here's hoping that enough uproar is generated that Trump and co. think again about making their predictable/alarming move on limiting freedom of expression. 

We're assuming folk will have enough pointers not to need links, but will keep an eye on comments and can fill in any details!

P.S. Please note: for anyone whose kids watch, Ben forget to put special characters in the swear word at the death of the song, so heads-up on that.

When you upset the

Now gotta watch out what you say!
Don’t be critiquing
Or public speaking
Nod and agree

A smear might make you unhappy
There’s insults from bots and trolls
Abuse, when it lands, feels crappy

But if you get slurred as “Nazi”
And want to retaliate
It’s not the best self-defence, see,
To mimic a fascist state (uh oh!)

Freedom of speech
Freedom of speech
No more displeasing, only appeasing the FCC
They say it’s “easy way or hard”
He’s such a teaser, Brendon Carr!
Wielding his muzzle
Networks don’t struggle
Heel on the leash

Hypocrisy (hypocrisy!)
Hypocrisy (hypocrisy!)
Free speech believers 
Pulling the levers
Of the “thought police”
Using the regulator’s sway
Pressuring outlets what to say
Kimmel, near cancelled …
Colbert dismantled …
Goebbels-style glee

The left like to carp
The right like to bait
There’s truth in some lies
There’s threat in some hate
There’s innocent barbs
There’s hooks that incite

The ratings are in:
The sicker the mind,
The thinner the skin
From Caesar to Mao
From Stalin to now
Their ego’s quick to blow

You can browbeat a
Democracy

Up pops red hot Vice President Vance
Gives Europe sermons
While he pulls U-turns
Freedom of speech
Making things ‘great’ there
Stifling debate there
Freedom of speech

Each little measure
Building the pressure
Cow all the papers
Rat out your neighbours
Wish you all luck there

snippet.description:
It’s 1990, you’re fresh out of high school and not sure what to do with your life, so, obviously, you follow your buddy blindly into the US Marine Corps... What could go wrong? Inspired by a real manly story, BOOTS marches onto Netflix October 9.

Song: "Freedom! '90" by #GeorgeMichael covered by the San Diego Gay Men's Chorus

Add this to your watch list: https://www.netflix.com/BOOTS That’s a direct order!

BOOTS is a one-hour comedic drama that delivers an irreverent, off-beat take on the coming-of-age story. Set in the tough, unpredictable world of the 1990s US Marine Corps—when being gay in the military was still illegal—the series follows directionless, closeted Cameron Cope (#MilesHeizer) and his best friend Ray McAffey (Liam Oh), the son of a decorated Marine, as they join a diverse group of recruits. Together, this ensemble navigates the literal and metaphorical landmines of boot camp, forging unlikely bonds and discovering their true selves in an environment designed to push them to their limits. With sharp wit and plenty of heart, BOOTS is about friendship, resilience, and finding your place in the world—even when that world seems determined to keep you in line or leave you behind.

snippet.title: HAQ | Official Teaser | Yami Gautam Dhar, Emraan Hashmi | Suparn S Varma | In Cinemas 7th Nov
snippet.description:
Shazia Bano takes her husband Abbas to court after he abandons her and their children, sparking a national battle over faith, women’s rights, and justice. Inspired by the landmark Supreme Court judgement of Mohd. Ahmed Khan vs. Shah Bano Begum. Haq is the story of one woman’s fight for her rights and justice. 

Releasing in cinemas on 7th November

HAQ is a fictionalized and dramatized version of events stated in the book titled ‘Bano: Bharat ki Beti’ written by Jigna Vora.

Cast- Yami Gautam, Emraan Hashmi, Vartika Singh, Danish Husain, Sheeba Chadha,
